{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641968"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:34:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:34:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17918"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17918"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.15,0.69,0,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10632"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77515"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10632"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17918"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63027"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10770"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24769"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24772"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77515"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old female has had recurrent urinary tract infections for the past 2 months. She has a significant family history of type 2 Diabetes Mellitus. Her General Practitioner decided to perform a random blood glucose - 10.5mmol/L.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about the diagnosis of type 2 diabetes is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Type 2 diabetes often presents with sudden onset of symptoms.","A glucose tolerance test requires a blood glucose level over 7 mmol/L at three hours after ingestion of 50g of glucose.","Glycosylated haemoglobin results from the exposure of haemoglobin to glucose, leading to glycosylation of the end amino groups of the alpha and beta polypeptide chains.","Glycosylated haemoglobin reflects short-term glucose control.","Diagnosis is confirmed with a fasting blood glucose level over 11 mmol/L on two separate occasions."],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlycosylated haemoglobin results from the exposure of haemoglobin to glucose, leading to glycosylation of the end amino groups of the alpha and beta polypeptide chains.\u003C/strong\u003E This process reflects the average blood glucose levels over the past three months, making it a useful measure for long-term glucose control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 diabetes often presents with sudden onset of symptoms\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The condition typically develops gradually, with polydipsia, polyuria, and fatigue appearing over time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnosis is confirmed with a fasting blood glucose level over 11 mmol/L on two separate occasions\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. A fasting blood glucose level of 7.0 mmol/L or higher on two separate occasions is used for diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA glucose tolerance test requires a blood glucose level over 7 mmol/L at three hours after ingestion of 50g of glucose\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The test typically involves a 75g glucose load, and a two-hour post-load glucose level of 11.1 mmol/L or higher is diagnostic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlycosylated haemoglobin reflects short-term glucose control\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. It reflects long-term glucose control over approximately three months.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type 2 diabetes is often insidious in onset, with symptoms developing gradually.","Diagnosis of type 2 diabetes is primarily based on fasting blood glucose, oral glucose tolerance test, or HbA1c levels.","Glycosylated haemoglobin (HbA1c) reflects long-term glucose control over approximately three months."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020 Oct 13;10(4):174-188. doi: 10.4103/ajm.ajm_53_20. PMID: 33437689; PMCID: PMC7791288","Galicia-Garcia U, Benito-Vicente A, Jebari S, Larrea-Sebal A, Siddiqi H, Uribe KB, Ostolaza H, Mart\u00edn C. Pathophysiology of Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus. Int J Mol Sci. 2020 Aug 30;21(17):6275. doi: 10.3390/ijms21176275. PMID: 32872570; PMCID: PMC7503727","Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020 Oct 13;10(4):174-188. doi: 10.4103/ajm.ajm_53_20. PMID: 33437689; PMCID: PMC7791288"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63027"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17918"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63027"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T10:54:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T10:54:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10632"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77515"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type